The tradition, as given by Dionysius, is this, that Aeneas had two sons, Ascanius by Creusa, and Silvius by Lavinia. The son of Ascanius was Iulus, who. being supplanted by his uncle Silvius, did not succeed to the crown at his father’s death, but‘lived in the odour ofsancffly, and became the founder ofthe Julian gens. Several other Roman gentes had the vanity to deduce their descent from demigods or heroes, (in the Greek sense of the word); the gen-s Fabia, for instance, from Hercules and a daughter of Evander.
